From: Paige Gabhart [mailto:pgabhart@...] 
Sent: Saturday, February 19, 2005 2:19 PM
To: &#39;stbetta@...&#39;
Subject: Kingsley

Steve:

I was looking at your font, &quot;Kingsley,&quot; today, and I find the letter
shapes quite attractive.  However, I have one question, which I don&#39;t
remember being mentioned previously in any posts.  The letter for the
long &quot;e&quot; sound differs from the Quikscript manual.  In the manual, the
second stroke is vertical, whereas, your font makes the letter
bilaterally symmetrical through a vertical plane, i.e. the second
strokes is a mirror image of the initial stroke.  Was this simply a
mistake, or is there some reason you designed it this way?  If the
latter is true, would it be possible to correct it?

I find it confusing because it doesn&#39;t look like the letter should look
to me, and when I read something displayed in this font, it slows down
my reading.  Furthermore, in my opinion, it is too easy to confuse with
the symbol used for &quot;oo&quot; in ooze.


Paige

&quot;I despise a world which does not feel that music is a higher revelation
than all wisdom and philosophy.&quot; 
-Ludwig van Beethoven 


